<section xml:id="section-assignment-week11">
  <title>Week 11 Assignment</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{n!}{(n+3)!}
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=1}^\infty \left( n + \frac{1}{n} \right)^{-n} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=2}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n(n^3 + 2n)}{n^2 + 7n} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence. (The integral test can be
        use here, but the integral is a bit tricky. One way to solve
        the integral involves the substitution <m>u = \ln x^3</m>
        followed by integration by parts) (6) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{\ln (n^3)}{n^2} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence. (Use the ratio test. The
        challenge here is all about factorial algebra. Match up the
        various factorials and see how you can cancel terms to get a
        reasonable limit.) (6) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(n!)^2((2n)!)^2}{(n^2 + 2n)!(n+1)!} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{1 - e^{-\frac{n^2 + 3n}{n}}}{n^2} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Assume that <m>a_n \gt 0</m> and that the following series
        converges. (12)
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=1}^\infty a_n 
      </me>
      <p>
        Here are some series which are based on the series we already
        have. Determine if these alterations converge or diverge. Give
        clear answers and reasons, either using convergence test or
        other argument from the definition and properties of series. 
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \amp \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{1}{a_n} \amp 
          \amp \sum_{n=1}^\infty 12a_n  \amp 
          \amp \sum_{n=1}^\infty e^{a_n} \amp 
          \amp \sum_{n=1}^\infty (a_n)^2
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
  </ol>
</section>
